libx11: fix -Wmaybe-uninitialized / -Werror=array-bounds under LTO and two
        latent correctness bugs uncovered by them.

This patch resolves the diagnostics that abort the GCC LTO build of libX11 and,
in doing so, fixes two genuine bugs (not merely warning suppressions):

1) src/xlibi18n/XDefaultOMIF.c  (_XmbDefaultTextExtents)
   -Wmaybe-uninitialized on overall.{lbearing,rbearing,width,ascent,descent}.
   XTextExtents() always fully initialises 'overall' (glyph loop, or its
   nfound==0 zeroing branch), so this is a genuine LTO false positive: the
   optimiser cannot see through the call. Zero-initialise the aggregate at
   declaration; the store is elided wherever the compiler can prove it dead.

2) src/XlibInt.c  (_XGetHostname, inlined into XSetWMProperties)
   -Werror=array-bounds: strncpy() copies strlen(name.nodename) bytes, and when
   inlined with the caller's maxlen (256) the array-bounds pass cannot prove the
   read stays within nodename[65]. Clamp the length to sizeof(name.nodename)
   BEFORE the maxlen clamp, making the source read provably in-range, and use
   memcpy() for the exact (now bounded) length. Behaviour is unchanged for all
   valid hostnames.

3) modules/im/ximcp/imDefIm.c  (_XimProtoSetIMValues, XIM_OVERFLOW path)
   -Wmaybe-uninitialized on preply. This exposed a REAL bug: on XIM_OVERFLOW the
   oversized reply is re-read into the small fixed BUFSIZE *stack* buffer 'reply'
   instead of the freshly Xmalloc()'d 'preply' sized for 'len'. That both
   overflowed the stack buffer (len > BUFSIZE by definition here) and left
   'preply' uninitialised before it is dereferenced. Read into 'preply' and
   guard the allocation, exactly as the sibling _XimProtoGetIMValues() does.

